# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ptasie-mleczko
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/agar-agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] An **aircraft livery** is a set of comprehensive insignia comprising color, graphic, and typographical identifiers which operators (airlines, governments, air forces and occasionally private and corporate owners) apply to their aircraft.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] As aircraft liveries evolved in the years after the Second World War, they became a leading subset of the emerging disciplines of corporate identity and branding and among the most prominent examples of fashion.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] They have provided an arena for the work of distinguished designers and eminent lay people like Raymond Loewy, Alexander Girard, and Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The term is an adaptation of the word *livery*: the uniform-style clothing worn by servants of wealthy families and government representatives until the early/mid-20th century.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] With the advent of stagecoaches, railway trains, and steamships, the term livery spread to their decoration.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Since the 1950s, elements of airline liveries permeated ground vehicles, advertising, proprietary airport furniture, airline promotional materials and aircrew uniforms in an increasingly integrated manner, spreading to airline websites in the 1990s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Since the 1950s and 1960s, aircraft liveries have usually been uniform livery across an entire fleet.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] One-off custom-designs might be applied from time to time to individual fleet members to highlight set occasions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Painting in multiple layers has evolved into the application of a basecoat-clearcoat system.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The new method improves gloss, color retention, and drying speed.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] It can also double the life of the coating and weigh possibly 30% less than multiple layers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Paint can weigh up to 1,000 lb (450 kg) per aircraft.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Decals and/or stickers are used for geometrically challenging elements such as titles and logos.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] To paint an A380, 24 painters were needed over two weeks to apply 2,300 L (610 US gal) of paint in five coats for British Airways, to cover 3,500 m2 (38,000 sq ft) with 650 kg (1,430 lb).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Emirates stripped and repainted one in 15 days with 34 people including seven days for painting, covering 3,076 m2 (33,110 sq ft) with 1,100 kg (2,400 lb) in seven coats.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Airline liveries involve set individual elements.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The airline's name is usually set in a specific style.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] This is closely defined by typographical designers as a logotype.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Size varies according to fleet member; the larger the aircraft, the larger the titling.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Since type is designed to be customarily read from a flat surface, airline livery type is often modified to fit curved aircraft surfaces.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The specifications result in a logotype: a cliche of type whose characteristics remain unchanged.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The airline's monogram or emblem is defined in terms of geometry by graphic designers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The resulting specification is called a logo.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Logos are also modified to fit curved surfaces and appear identical from diverse viewing angles.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The colour or colours are specified in terms of colour matching and standardisation systems like Pantone or Federal Standard 595.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The resulting specification is called a colourway.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Individual aircraft types most often have individually designed liveries which appear to be identical, but are not quite the same as those applied to other aircraft types operated by the same airline.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Uniform liveries became generally adopted by the 1950s and '60s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Before then, individual airlines, notably Aeroflot and some US carriers like Delta Air Lines, used custom liveries designed for each individual aircraft type they operated.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Aeroflot abandoned the practice as late as 1974, adopting a uniform livery across its fleet.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Until after the Second World War, the "default solution" for aircraft livery design was to leave the aircraft exterior unpainted and decorated only with the airline's title, plus possibly an emblem or monogram.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] When the world's first all-metal airliners, such as the Boeing 247, Douglas DC-2, and Douglas DC-3, entered service in the 1930s, the sleekness of their shiny exteriors provided an imaginative canvas for livery design.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] At the time, paint was expensive, fairly heavy, had relatively poor adherence to metal, and was prone to early bleaching, mechanical, and chemical damage; leaving the aircraft skin largely unpainted was logical and economical.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] As corrosion and paint research advanced and airliner lives lengthened, airframers began applying advanced primers and treatments to airliners during manufacture.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Many airframers insisted on overall corrosion protection remaining in place throughout an airliner's service life, or at least throughout its diverse guarantee periods.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] This made bare metal liveries problematic; they began giving way to painted exteriors by the mid-1960s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] To ensure longevity, bare metal liveries involved intensive polishing and waxing during manufacture and in service.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Nevertheless, the bare metal era survived into the 21st century, although composite-material airliners like the Boeing 787 Dreamliner and all Airbus jets cannot achieve the bare metal look without paint due to their material, which does not have metallic luster.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The most notable proponent of the bare metal look, American Airlines, adopted a painted livery in 2013.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Cargo carriers like Cargolux, Flying Tiger Line, JAL Japan Airlines Cargo, Korean Air Cargo, and Seaboard World Airlines often claimed that their bare metal liveries save weight.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Counterclaims stated that extra maintenance costs cancel this benefit.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Among the earliest recognisable elements of aircraft liveries was the cheatline.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] A cheatline is a decorative horizontal stripe applied to the sides of an aircraft fuselage.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The etymology of the term stems from "cheating the eye" because the first cheatlines aimed to streamline aircraft visually by reducing the staccato impact of their cabin windows.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] US carriers like the predecessors of United Air Lines and TWA (then Transcontinental and Western Airlines) adopted cheatlines as early as the 1920s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Cheatlines may be in single ("rules") or multiple ("tramlines") bands, and in one or more colours.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Cheatlines migrated from the window line to below or occasionally above it.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] They also melded other decorative elements like stylised lightning bolts, feathers, moustaches, national flags and colours, and elements of the airline's title and emblem.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Cheatlines declined in popularity from the 1970s onward.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Today, they often appear in liveries designed to evoke a retro aesthetic or convey a sense of tradition (heritage/retro liveries).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] However, some major airlines continue to employ cheatlines in their standard liveries, such as Air China and Singapore Airlines, where they serve as enduring elements of corporate branding rather than retro stylisation.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 2023, Saudia introduced its current brand identity, which included reverting to a cheatline scheme similar to those worn by its aircraft between the 1970s and early 2000s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] One noticeable difference, however, is that the cheatline itself was moved to beneath the windows, instead of being applied across them.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In aircraft livery design, a "hockey stick" means a continuation of the cheatline which is rotated through an angle so as to sweep upwards over the tail fin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Among the first hockey stick liveries were the Eastern Airlines' 1964 jet livery and Alitalia's 1970 livery.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Hockey stick aircraft liveries remained in fashion until the late 1970s/early '80s with Cathay Pacific still having them as late as 1994.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 1965, Braniff International Airways hired Alexander Girard to revamp their corporate identity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The eventual design involved painting the entire aircraft fuselage in one of several single bold colourways.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The airline title was logotyped as "Braniff International" in custom designed italic capitals, with the initials pasted across airliner tail fins.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The livery was part of a comprehensive corporate identity revamp also involving dedicated airport lounges and including a short-lived "space helmet" headgear for cabin staff.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 1969, Court Line Aviation hired Peter Murdoch to revamp its corporate identity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The resulting design included decorating each fleet member in one of five different colourways within a hockeystick scheme.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The airline name was logotyped as "court" in custom designed lowercase italics, and could easily be changed to 'liat' when individual aircraft transferred to Court Line's Caribbean subsidiary LIAT Leeward Islands Air Transport.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Another all-over colour livery was adopted by airline group British Air Services in late 1970.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Group members Northeast Airlines and Cambrian Airlines had their aircraft painted white/grey/yellow and white/grey/orange.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Related pink and green liveries were designed for group members Scottish and Channel Islands Airways, but never saw service use.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] From the 1970s, the overall colour idea began to spread worldwide, largely in the form of "Eurowhite" liveries in which white was the dominant colour.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] A side benefit of the overall white look was that it helped airline asset management.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] It did so by facilitating the hiring-out (chartering in 1960s parlance or leasing from the 1970s) of individual fleet members during seasonal traffic troughs or economic downturns.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Overall white aircraft could readily accept major elements of lessee liveries, and could equally rapidly revert to lessor liveries on return.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Notable early Eurowhite liveries included UTA Union de Transports Aériens's early 1970s livery and Air France's 1976 livery.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Pan Am's 1983 “Billboard” livery was among the first Eurowhite schemes outside Europe.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Except for a very brief Air France Pepsi logojet example, all Concorde liveries were predominantly Eurowhite-based, as this reduced heat absorption.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The Braniff 1967 livery (see All-Over Color above) was also often dubbed "Jellybean." Jellybean liveries involve multiple alternative colourways in which entire aircraft or parts of them are decorated.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] British Airways’ 1997 ethnic liveries were celebrated Jellybean examples.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The 1970s saw the emergence of Billboard liveries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] This places the airline title centrestage in the livery, often at the expense of the cheatline.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Early adopters of Billboard liveries included UTA Union de Transports Aériens (UTA), Seaboard World Airlines, Hughes Airwest, and LOT Polish Airlines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Western's and Pan Am's final liveries were celebrated Billboard examples.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In the 1990s and 2000s, two of the three main airline alliances adopted Billboard liveries for application to selected aircraft operated by alliance member airlines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Low-cost carriers such as Ryanair and Spirit Airlines have also employed the use of Billboard liveries on their aircraft.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Commemorative liveries are used to celebrate a milestone in an airline’s history, including anniversaries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 2015, KLM painted a Boeing 777 in a special 'Orange Pride' livery, commemorating the country's national colour, which faded into the standard KLM blue livery.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 2016, Aeroméxico painted a Boeing 787 in a special livery inspired by the Quetzalcōātl.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The aircraft was used to transport athletes and delegation to the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] In 2026, Lufthansa unveiled a celebratory livery for multiple aircraft to commemorate the airline's 100 year anniversary.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] A heritage livery is a restoration of a past livery for publicity purposes or to stress the length of an airline's experience or tradition.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Airlines often apply and paint specialized liveries to their standard airline liveries and logos of their aircraft.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Southwest Airlines is famous for its various liveries promoting Sea World (painted to resemble an Orca), various US states where Southwest has operations (painted to resemble the states' flags), and other entities such as the NBA and the Ronald McDonald House.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Boeing painted a pre-delivery 747-8 to commemorate the Seattle Seahawks' 2014 National Football Conference Championship and appearance in Super Bowl XLVIII.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Alaska Airlines has painted several aircraft in its fleet with promotional liveries for other companies such as its Disneyland, Star Wars: Galaxy's Edge, and "Go Cougs" liveries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] All Nippon Airways has featured a number of aircraft in a promotional Pokémon livery, known as the Pokémon Jet.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] EVA Air partnered with Sanrio to create a number of "Hello Kitty Jets." Low-cost carriers like VietJet Air have designed its standard liveries so every aircraft are available to be instantly featured with promotional liveries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Each of the 3 major airline alliances (Star Alliance, SkyTeam, and Oneworld) have standard commemorative liveries worn by some of its members' aircraft.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The standard Star Alliance livery was introduced in 2002, debuting with Asiana Airlines, however previous variations had been used since the alliance's founding in 1997.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] It features a white fuselage with the Star Alliance name painted in bold billboard titles, the airline's own logo underneath on the forward fuselage, and a black tail with the Star Alliance logo.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Some variations exist, including Air New Zealand, which uses an all black fuselage and white titles.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The SkyTeam livery was unveiled in 2009 with Delta Air Lines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] It features a silver fuselage with the SkyTeam title on the front section of the fuselage, and the airline's own logo underneath.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The back portion features the blue SkyTeam ribbon, and the tail is dark blue with the SkyTeam logo.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The standard Oneworld livery was introduced in 2009, however some airlines had been using their own promotional liveries before this.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The livery features the Oneworld name in large billboard titles across the fuselage, with a larger Oneworld logo, and the airline's own titles underneath.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Unlike the other two alliances, the airline retains their standard tail fin and other livery elements.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] To offer air travelers what appears as a seamless association with an airline that is much larger, more prominent, well known, or publicly perceived as more safe, major North American airlines have developed a system of affiliate air carriers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] These feeder airlines operate regional jets and other types of smaller utility air-taxi type aircraft, typically painted in ways that mimic (whether through distinctive fonts, colour combinations, or cheatline arrangements) the respective liveries of the operators with which they are affiliated.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] They may carry sub-branding such as *Airlink*, *Connection*, *Eagle*, or *Express* juxtaposed with the more widely recognised carrier name.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] A recent trend in North America is for regional airlines d/b/a *Express*, *Eagle,* or *Connection,* to operate the aircraft in full mainline airline markings, leaving the operating regional airlines name in only very small letters, close to the forward entry door.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Such brandings noted to cause confusion among travelers, as in the case of the Colgan Air Continental Connection Flight 3407 crash in which people identified the flight with Continental Airlines, although it was actually flown by Colgan Air.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Air transports of heads of state and government are often painted in unique color schemes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The U.S. president's aircraft, Air Force One, uses a light-blue and sky-blue color scheme, with the seal of the president of the United States just above the front gear and the flag of the United States on the tailfin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] The livery was designed by French-American industrial designer Raymond Loewy at the instigation, and with the help of, then-First Lady Jacqueline Kennedy.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Aircraft carrying state or government leaders are often liveried in national colors or the insignia of a particular government office.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Military aircraft often make use of aircraft camouflage to make the aircraft more difficult to see in the air and on the ground.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] This form of camouflage makes use of light and color patterns, and is dependent upon environmental conditions and is mainly effective against human observers, though some electronic visual acquisition systems can be affected.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Visual camouflage does not protect an aircraft against radar location or heat-seeking electronics.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Since the release of MIL-STD-2161 in 1993, the US Navy's tactical aircraft use a color scheme designed to reduce visual detection that consists of shades of flat gray with exterior markings applied in a contrasting shade of gray.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Note that the stated purpose of this document is to standardize paint schemes and application of naval insignia and markings.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Aircraft camouflage was first used during World War I and was employed extensively during the first half of World War II.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] After radar detection systems were developed, aircraft camouflage became less important to the Allies, and a number of late-war Allied aircraft were brought to battle with no camouflage.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Subsequent camouflage schemes, when used, concentrated on hiding the aircraft from aerial observation while it was resting on or flying near the ground, or they used a light, neutral color to inhibit detection while in the air.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aircraft-livery] Modern camouflage schemes have experimented with light-emitting active camouflage systems which seek to conceal the aircraft from human vision or to blur or confuse optical observation by electronic means.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Remizov was reared in the merchant milieu of Moscow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] As a student of the Moscow University, he was involved in the radical politics and spent eight years in prison and Siberian exile.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] At that time, he developed a keen interest in Russian folklore and married a student of ancient Russian art, who brought him in contact with the Roerichs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] In 1905, he settled in Saint Petersburg and started to imitate medieval folk tales.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] His self-professed ambition was to catch "the bitterness and absurdity of folklore imagination".
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Remizov's whimsical stylizations of the saints' lives were ignored at first, partly due to their florid and turgid language, but his more traditional prose works set in the underworld of Russian cities gained him a great deal of publicity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] In his satirical novella *The History of the Tinkling Cymbal and Sounding Brass* (1910/1922) Remizov depicted the eccentricities and superstitions of rural sectarians.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Another striking work of this period is "The Sacrifice", a Gothic horror story in which "a ghostly double of a father comes to kill his innocent daughter in the mistaken belief that she is a chicken".
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] By the time of the Russian Revolution, Remizov had concentrated on imitating more or less obscure works of medieval Russian literature.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] He responded to the revolution by the *Lay of the Ruin of the Russian Land*, a paraphrase of the 13th-century work bemoaning the Mongol invasion of Russia.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] In 1921 he moved to Berlin and then in 1923 - to Paris, where he published an account of his attitudes towards the revolution under the title *Whirlwind Russia* (1927).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] During his years in exile, Remizov brought out a number of bizarre works, featuring demons and nightmare creatures.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] The writer also developed a keen interest in *dreams* and wrote a few works on the subject that involved prominent figures of Russian literature (Gogol, Dostoyevsky and others).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Although he was so prolific many of his works failed to find a publisher (in fact, from 1931 to 1952 there was not a single book published).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Remizov was also the first Russian modernist author to attract the attention of the luminaries of the Parisian literary world, such as James Joyce.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] His reputation suffered a decline when, following World War II, he announced his interest in returning to the Soviet Union and even obtained a Soviet passport (which he did not have a chance to use).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] After that, Remizov was abhorred by the émigré litterateurs, the most famous of whom, Vladimir Nabokov, used to say that the only nice thing about Remizov was that he really lived in the world of literature.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] The years 1952 to 1957 saw a number of Remizov's books published, though only a very limited number of copies were printed.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Along with Andrei Bely, Remizov was one of the most famous Russian modernist writers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] He became known for his experimental *skaz* techniques and "underground Dostoevskianism".
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aleksey-remizov] Mirsky notes, Remizov's works influenced Yevgeny Zamyatin, Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy and Mikhail Prishvin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Alexander Afanasyev was born in the town of Boguchar in the Voronezh Governorate of the Russian Empire (modern-day Voronezh Oblast of Russia) into a family of modest means.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] His mother Varvara Mikhailovna Afanasyeva came from common people.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Alexander was her seventh child; she became very ill after giving birth and died by the end of the year.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In three years the family moved to Bobrov, Voronezh where Alexander spent his childhood.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He became addicted to reading early in his life, having access to the well-stocked library left by his grandfather (a member of the Russian Bible Society), as well as to various magazines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1837 he was sent to the Voronezh male gymnasium, and in 1844 he entered the Law Faculty of the University of Moscow which he finished in 1848.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] There he attended the lectures of Konstantin Kavelin, Timofey Granovsky, Sergey Solovyov, Stepan Shevyryov, Osip Bodyansky and Fyodor Buslaev.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He published a series of articles on government economy during the times of Peter the Great, on the Pskov Judicial Charter and other topics in the *Sovremennik* and *Otechestvennye Zapiski* magazines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Despite being one of the most promising students, he failed to become a professor.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] The conservative Minister of National Enlightenment, Count Sergey Uvarov, who oversaw the final exams, attacked Afanasyev's essay which discussed the role of autocracy in the development of Russian criminal law during the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1849 Konstantin Kavelin helped him to get a place at the Moscow's Main Archive Directorate under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Empire, and here Afanasyev worked for the next 13 years.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] During that time he met many people of science and culture, collected a lot of ancient books and manuscripts that formed a huge library.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] His articles, reviews, ethnographical and historical works regularly appeared in the leading Russian magazines, newspapers, almanacs and scientific periodicals.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] His essays on Russian satire of the 18th century and on the works of prominent writers and publishers resulted in an 1859 monograph "Русские сатирические журналы 1769–1774 г." ("Russian Satirical Magazines of 1769–1774"), published in 'Otechestvennye Zapiski' (Nos.3, 4 of 1855; No.6 of 1859).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1855 he headed the state commission responsible for publication of legislative, historical and literary works.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] From 1858 to 1861 he also worked as the main editor of the short-lived magazine "Bibliographical Notes"" which actually served as a cover for collecting materials, censored and revolutionary literature for the socialist in exile Alexander Herzen.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1862 the authorities arrested the Narodnik Nikolay Chernyshevsky, while other people associated with Herzen, including Afanasiev, came under suspicion.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] His flat was searched, and while nothing was revealed, he still lost his place at the Moscow Archives.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] After his dismissal he could not find a stable job for several years and had to sell his library to feed his family.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] After that he worked as a secretary at the Moscow City Duma and at the Moscow Congress of Justices of the Peace while continuing his ethnographical research.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He wrote a large theoretical work (three tomes of 700 pages each) – "The Poetic Outlook of Slavs about Nature" – which came out between 1865 and 1869.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1870 his *Русские детские сказки* (Russian Children's Fairy Tales) were published.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Afanasyev spent his last years living in penury.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He died in Moscow aged 45, suffering from tuberculosis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He was buried at the Pyatnitskoye cemetery.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Afanasyev became interested in old Russian and Slav traditions and stories in the 1850s ("folklore" as an area of study did not exist at the time).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] His early scholarly articles, including – "Ведун и ведьма" ("Wizard and Witch", published in "Комета", 1851); "Языческие предания об острове Буяне" ("Pagan legends of Buyan Island", published in "Временнике общ. ист. и древ. росс." of 1858 No.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] 9) – drew upon the so-called Mythological school that treated legends and tales as a mine of information for the study of more ancient pagan mythology (see his definitive work on the subject "Поэтические воззрения славян на природу" ("The Poetic Outlook on Nature by the Slavs", 1865–1869).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In such an interpretation, he regarded the fairy tale *Vasilisa the Beautiful* as depicting the conflict between the sunlight (Vasilisa), the storm (her stepmother), and dark clouds (her stepsisters).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In the early 1850s, being already known for his articles, Afanasyev began to think about a collection of folk tales.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He was then asked by the Russian Geographical Society (ethnography section) of Saint Petersburg to publish the folktales archives that the Society had been in possession of for about ten years.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] These archives are at the start of his *Collection*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He added to them the enormous collection of Vladimir Dal (about 1000 texts), from which he kept 148 numbers, finding the other ones too distorted, his own collection (of about 10 folktales from the Voronezh region), and a few other collections.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He added already published tales (such as *Maria Marievna*, *The Firebird*, *The Grey Wolf*, etc.), a few tales coming from epic songs, stories about the dead, a few medieval satirical texts (such as *The Shemiaka Sentence*), and anecdotes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He owes his prominent place in the history of Slavonic philology chiefly to these *Russian Fairy Tales* (*Народные русские сказки*), published between 1855 and 1863, and inspired by the famous collection of the Brothers Grimm.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] From the scientific point of view, his collection goes further.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He had at his disposal a lot of contributors, he tried to give the source and place where the tale was told, he never tried to give any definitive version of a folktale: so, if he gathered seven versions of one folk type, he edited them all (this is the case for The Firebird for instance).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] In 1860 a scandal was provoked following the publication of the "Русские народные легенды" ("Russian Folk Legends", 1860), a collection of folk tales from all over the country based on the lives of Jesus and Christian saints.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] The result was a unique blend of Christianity with paganism and social undertones.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Some of them were labeled unorthodox by the Most Holy Synod and the book was officially banned.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] He also prepared *Заветные сказки* ("Treasured Tales"), an assortment of redacted tales from "Русские народные легенды" plus other potential controversial stories – published as *Russian Forbidden Tales* in Switzerland anonymously because of their obscene and anticlerical subject matter.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Prior to Afanasyev's works in the 1850s, only a few attempts had ever been made to record or study the folk beliefs of peasant Russia.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Though written Church Slavonic had existed since the 10th century, it was used almost solely by the church and only for parochial written works.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] It was not until the 18th and 19th centuries that a sizable body of secular literature developed in vernacular Russian.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] Thus, Afanasyev's collections made a highly valuable contribution to the dissemination and legitimization of Russian culture and folk belief.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/alexander-afanasyev] The influence of these folk tales can be seen in the works of many writers and composers, notably Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov (*Sadko, The Snow Maiden*) and Igor Stravinsky (*The Firebird*, *Petrushka*, and *L'Histoire du soldat*).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Also known as "The Father of Comedy" and "the Prince of Ancient Comedy", Aristophanes wrote plays that often dealt with real-life figures, including Euripides and Alcibiades, and contemporary events, such as the Peloponnesian War.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He has been said to recreate the life of ancient Athens more convincingly than any other author.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] His plays are characterized by preposterous premises, explicit language, wordplays, and political satire.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] His powers of ridicule were feared and acknowledged by influential contemporaries; Plato singled out Aristophanes's play *The Clouds* as slander that contributed to the trial and subsequent condemning to death of Socrates, although other satirical playwrights had also caricatured the philosopher.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes's second play, *The Babylonians* (now lost), was denounced by Cleon as a slander against the Athenian *polis*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It is possible that the case was argued in court, but details of the trial are not recorded and Aristophanes caricatured Cleon mercilessly in his subsequent plays, especially *The Knights*, the first of many plays that he directed himself.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] An Athenian citizen, Aristophanes came from the deme of Kydathenaion, which was part of the Attic tribe (*phyle*) of Pandionis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] His father was Philippus and his mother was Zenodora.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In antiquity, his family was assumed to have connections with the island of Aegina.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Little is known about Aristophanes's life, his plays being the main source of biographical information.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It was conventional in Old Comedy for the chorus to speak on behalf of the author during an address called the *parabasis*, where some biographical facts can usually be found.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These facts, however, relate almost entirely to his career as a dramatist and the plays contain few clear and unambiguous clues about his personal beliefs or his private life.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He was a comic poet in an age when it was conventional for the playwright to also serve as the play's director (*didaskalos*).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The term literally means "teacher," referring primarily to his role in training the chorus in rehearsal, but perhaps also covered his relationship with the audience as a commentator on significant issues.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes claimed to be writing for a clever and discerning audience, yet he also declared that "other times" would judge the audience according to its reception of his plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He sometimes boasts of his originality as a dramatist yet his plays consistently espouse opposition to radical new influences in Athenian society.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He caricatured leading figures in the arts (notably Euripides, whose influence on his own work however he once grudgingly acknowledged), in politics (especially the populist Cleon), and in philosophy/religion (where Socrates was the most obvious target).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Such caricatures seem to imply that Aristophanes was an old-fashioned conservative, yet that view of him leads to contradictions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It has been argued that Aristophanes produced plays mainly to entertain the audience and to win prestigious competitions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] His plays were written for production at the great dramatic festivals of Athens, the Lenaia and City Dionysia, where they were judged and awarded prizes in competition with the works of other comic dramatists.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] An elaborate series of lotteries, designed to prevent prejudice and corruption, reduced the voting judges at the City Dionysia to just five.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These judges probably reflected the mood of the audiences yet there is much uncertainty about the composition of those audiences.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The theatres were certainly huge, with seating for at least 10,000 at the Theatre of Dionysus.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The day's program at the City Dionysia for example was crowded, with three tragedies and a satyr play ahead of a comedy, but it is possible that many of the poorer citizens (typically the main supporters of demagogues like Cleon) occupied the festival holiday with other pursuits.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The conservative views expressed in the plays might therefore reflect the attitudes of the dominant group in an unrepresentative audience.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The production process might also have influenced the views expressed in the plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Throughout most of Aristophanes's career, the Chorus was essential to a play's success and it was recruited and funded by a *choregus*, a wealthy citizen appointed to the task by one of the archons.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] A choregus could regard his personal expenditure on the Chorus as a civic duty and a public honour, but Aristophanes showed in *The Knights* that wealthy citizens might regard civic responsibilities as punishment imposed on them by demagogues and populists like Cleon.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Thus the political conservatism of the plays may reflect the views of the wealthiest section of Athenian society, on whose generosity all dramatists depended for putting on their plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] When Aristophanes's first play *The Banqueters* was produced, Athens was an ambitious, imperial power and the Peloponnesian War was only in its fourth year.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] His plays often express pride in the achievement of the older generation (the victors at Marathon) yet they are not jingoistic, and they are staunchly opposed to the war with Sparta.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The plays are particularly scathing in criticism of war profiteers, among whom populists such as Cleon figure prominently.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] By the time his last play was produced (around 386 BC) Athens had been defeated in war, its empire had been dismantled and it had undergone a transformation from being the political to the intellectual centre of Greece.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes was part of this transformation and he shared in the intellectual fashions of the period—the structure of his plays evolves from Old Comedy until, in his last surviving play, *Wealth II*, it more closely resembles New Comedy.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] However it is uncertain whether he led or merely responded to changes in audience expectations.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes won second prize at the City Dionysia in 427 BC with his first play *The Banqueters* (now lost).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He won first prize there with his next play, *The Babylonians* (also now lost).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It was usual for foreign dignitaries to attend the City Dionysia, and *The Babylonians* caused some embarrassment for the Athenian authorities since it depicted the cities of the Delian League as slaves grinding at a mill.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Some influential citizens, notably Cleon, reviled the play as slander against the *polis* and possibly took legal action against the author.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes repeatedly savages Cleon in his later plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] But these satirical diatribes appear to have had no effect on Cleon's political career—a few weeks after the performance of *The Knights*—a play full of anti-Cleon jokes—Cleon was elected to the prestigious board of ten generals.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Cleon also seems to have had no real power to limit or control Aristophanes: the caricatures of him continued up to and even beyond his death.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In the absence of clear biographical facts about Aristophanes, scholars make educated guesses based on interpretation of the language in the plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Inscriptions and summaries or comments by Hellenistic and Byzantine scholars can also provide useful clues.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes's use of directors complicates our reliance on the plays as sources of biographical information, because apparent self-references might have been made with reference to his directors instead.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Thus, for example, a statement by the chorus in *The Acharnians* seems to indicate that the "poet" had a close, personal association with the island of Aegina.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Comments made by the Chorus referring to Aristophanes in *The Clouds* have been interpreted as evidence that he can hardly have been more than 18 years old when his first play *The Banqueters* was produced.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The second parabasis in *Wasps* appears to indicate that he reached some kind of temporary accommodation with Cleon following either the controversy over *The Babylonians* or a subsequent controversy over *The Knights*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It has been inferred from statements in *The Clouds* and *Peace* that Aristophanes was prematurely bald.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes was probably victorious at least once at the City Dionysia, with *Babylonians* in 427, and at least three times at the Lenaia, with *The Acharnians* in 425, *Knights* in 424, and *Frogs* in 405.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] *Frogs* in fact won the unique distinction of a repeat performance at a subsequent festival.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] A son of Aristophanes, Araros, was also a comic poet and he could have been heavily involved in the production of his father's play *Wealth II* in 388.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Araros is also thought to have been responsible for the posthumous performances of the now lost plays *Aeolosicon II* and *Cocalus*, and it is possible that the last of these won the prize at the City Dionysia in 387.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It appears that a second son, Philippus, was twice victorious at the Lenaia and he could have directed some of Eubulus's comedies.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] A third son was called either Nicostratus or Philetaerus, and a man by the latter name appears in the catalogue of Lenaia victors with two victories, the first probably in the late 370s.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes survived The Peloponnesian War, two oligarchic revolutions and two democratic restorations; this has been interpreted as evidence that he was not actively involved in politics, despite his highly political plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He was probably appointed to the Council of Five Hundred for a year at the beginning of the fourth century, but such appointments were very common in democratic Athens.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Plato's *The Symposium* appears to be a useful source of biographical information about Aristophanes, but its reliability is open to doubt.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It purports to be a record of conversations at a dinner party at which both Aristophanes and Socrates are guests, held some seven years after the performance of *The Clouds*, the play in which Socrates was cruelly caricatured.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] One of the guests, Alcibiades, even quotes from the play when teasing Socrates over his appearance and yet there is no indication of any ill-feeling between Socrates and Aristophanes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Plato was only a boy when the events in *The Symposium* are supposed to have occurred and it is possible that his Aristophanes is in fact based on a reading of the plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] For example, conversation among the guests turns to the subject of Love and Aristophanes explains his notion of it in terms of an amusing allegory, a device he often uses in his plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He is represented as suffering an attack of hiccups and this might be a humorous reference to the crude physical jokes in his plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He tells the other guests that he is quite happy to be thought amusing but he is wary of appearing ridiculous.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] This fear of being ridiculed is consistent with his declaration in *The Knights* that he embarked on the career of comic playwright warily after witnessing the public contempt and ridicule that other dramatists had incurred.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The language of Aristophanes's plays, and in Old Comedy generally, was valued by ancient commentators as a model of the Attic dialect.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The orator Quintilian believed that the charm and grandeur of the Attic dialect made Old Comedy an example for orators to study and follow, and he considered it inferior in these respects only to the works of Homer.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] A revival of interest in the Attic dialect may have been responsible for the recovery and circulation of Aristophanes's plays during the fourth and fifth centuries AD, resulting in their survival today.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In Aristophanes's plays, the Attic dialect is couched in verse and his plays can be appreciated for their poetic qualities.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] For Aristophanes's contemporaries the works of Homer and Hesiod formed the cornerstones of Hellenic history and culture.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Thus poetry had a moral and social significance that made it an inevitable topic of comic satire.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes was very conscious of literary fashions and traditions and his plays feature numerous references to other poets.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These include not only rival comic dramatists such as Eupolis and Hermippus and predecessors such as Magnes, Crates and Cratinus, but also tragedians, notably Aeschylus, Sophocles and Euripides, all three of whom are mentioned in e.g.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes was the equal of these great tragedians in his subtle use of lyrics.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] He appears to have modelled his approach to language on that of Euripides in particular, so much so that the comic dramatist Cratinus labelled him a 'Euripidaristophanist' addicted to hair-splitting niceties.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] A full appreciation of Aristophanes's plays requires an understanding of the poetic forms he employed with virtuoso skill, and of their different rhythms and associations.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It can be argued that the most important feature of the language of the plays is imagery, particularly the use of similes, metaphors and pictorial expressions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In *The Knights*, for example, the ears of a character with selective hearing are represented as parasols that open and close.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In *The Frogs*, Aeschylus is said to compose verses in the manner of a horse rolling in a sandpit.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Some plays feature revelations of human perfectibility that are poetic rather than religious in character, such as the marriage of the hero Pisthetairos to Zeus's paramour in *The Birds* and the "recreation" of old Athens, crowned with roses, at the end of *The Knights*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The plays of Aristophanes are the only full-length examples of the genre of Old Comedy to have survived from antiquity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] This makes them centrally important to modern understandings of the genre.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] the departure of the Chorus and the actors, in song and dance celebrating the hero's victory and sometimes celebrating a symbolic marriage.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The rules of competition did not prevent a playwright arranging and adjusting these elements to suit his particular needs.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In *The Acharnians* and *Peace*, for example, there is no formal agon whereas in *The Clouds* there are two agons.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The parabasis is an address to the audience by the chorus or chorus leader while the actors leave or have left the stage.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] In this role, the chorus is sometimes out of character, as the author's voice, and sometimes in character, although these capacities are often difficult to distinguish.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Generally the parabasis occurs somewhere in the middle of a play and often there is a second parabasis towards the end.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The elements of a parabasis have been defined and named by scholars but it is probable that Aristophanes's own understanding was less formal.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The selection of elements can vary from play to play and it varies considerably within plays between first and second parabasis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The early plays (*The Acharnians* to *The Birds*) are fairly uniform in their approach however and the following elements of a parabasis can be found within them.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] This is usually a defense of the author's work and it includes criticism of the audience's attitude.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It is declaimed in long lines of 'anapestic tetrameters'.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes himself refers to the parabasis proper only as 'anapests'.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These are symmetrical scenes that mirror each other in meter and number of lines.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] They form part of the first parabasis and they often comprise the entire second parabasis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These are lyrics in a variety of meters, sung by the Chorus in the first parabasis as an invocation to the gods and as a comic interlude in the second parabasis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These are usually long lines of trochaic tetrameters.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Broadly political in their significance, they were probably spoken by the leader of the Chorus in character.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] These are songs that mirror the strophe/ode in meter, length and function.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] This is another declaimed passage and it mirrors the epirrhema in meter, length and function.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Textual corruption is probably the reason for the absence of the antistrophe in the second parabasis.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] However, there are several variations from the ideal even within the early plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] For example, the parabasis proper in *The Clouds* (lines 518–562) is composed in eupolidean meter rather than in anapests and the second parabasis includes a kommation but it lacks strophe, antistrophe and antepirrhema (*The Clouds* lines 1113–1130).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The second parabasis in *The Acharnians* lines 971–999 can be considered a hybrid parabasis/song (i.e. the declaimed sections are merely continuations of the strophe and antistrophe) and, unlike the typical parabasis, it seems to comment on actions that occur on stage during the address.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] An understanding of Old Comedy conventions such as the parabasis is necessary for a proper understanding of Aristophanes's plays; on the other hand, a sensitive appreciation of the plays is necessary for a proper understanding of the conventions.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Indeed, according to one ancient source (Platonius, c.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] 9th century AD), one of Aristophanes's last plays, *Aioliskon*, had neither a parabasis nor any choral lyrics (making it a type of Middle Comedy), while *Kolakos* anticipated all the elements of New Comedy, including a rape and a recognition scene.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Aristophanes seems to have had some appreciation of his formative role in the development of comedy, as indicated by his comment in *Clouds* that his audience would be judged by other times according to its reception of his plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] *Clouds* was awarded third (i.e. last) place after its original performance and the text that has come down to the modern age was a subsequent draft that Aristophanes intended to be read rather than acted.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The plays, in manuscript form, have been put to some surprising uses—as indicated earlier, they were used in the study of rhetoric on the recommendation of Quintilian and by students of the Attic dialect in the Fourth and Fifth Centuries AD.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] It is possible that Plato sent copies of the plays to Dionysius of Syracuse so that he might learn about Athenian life and government.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Latin translations of the plays by Andreas Divus (Venice 1528) were circulated widely throughout Europe in the Renaissance and these were soon followed by translations and adaptations in modern languages.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Racine, for example, drew *Les Plaideurs* (1668) from *The Wasps*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Goethe (who turned to Aristophanes for a warmer and more vivid form of comedy than he could derive from readings of Terence and Plautus) adapted a short play *Die Vögel* from *The Birds* for performance in Weimar.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The avant-gardist stage-director Karolos Koun directed a version of *The Birds* under the Acropolis in 1959 that established a trend in modern Greek history of breaking taboos through the voice of Aristophanes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The plays have a significance that goes beyond their artistic function, as historical documents that open the window on life and politics in classical Athens, in which respect they are perhaps as important as the writings of Thucydides.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The artistic influence of the plays is immeasurable.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] They have contributed to the history of European theatre and that history in turn shapes our understanding of the plays.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Thus for example the operettas of Gilbert and Sullivan can give us insights into Aristophanes's plays and similarly the plays can give us insights into the operettas.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Listed below are some of the many works influenced (more or less) by Aristophanes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Sommerstein believes that although there are good translations of Aristophanes's comedies, none could be flawless, "for there is much truth in the paradox that the only really perfect translation is the original." Nevertheless, there are competent, respectable translations in many languages.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] Most of these are traditionally referred to by abbreviations of their *Latin* titles; Latin remains a customary language of scholarship in classical studies.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/aristophanes] The standard modern edition of the fragments is Rudolf Kassel and Colin François Lloyd Austin's *Poetae Comici Graeci* III.2.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] Thuras and Foer met in 2007, and soon discussed ideas for a different kind of atlas, featuring places not commonly found in guidebooks.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] They hired a web designer in 2008 and launched *Atlas Obscura* in 2009.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] Annetta Black was the site's first senior editor.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In 2010, the site organized the first of the international events known as Obscura Day.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] Eliza Swann has also taught an online course on alchemy and related practices through Atlas Obscura.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] Sommer Mathis (formerly of *The Atlantic*'s CityLab) was the site's editor-in-chief from 2017 to 2020.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] She was succeeded by Samir Patel, formerly of *Archaeology* magazine, who became the site's editorial director in 2020 and editor-in-chief in 2021.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In October 2014, *Atlas Obscura* hired journalist David Plotz as its CEO.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] David Plotz was the site's CEO for five years (October 2014 – November 2019).
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] Warren Webster, former president and CEO of digital publisher *Coveteur*, and co-founder of website *Patch*, assumed the position in March 2020.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In 2015, *Atlas Obscura* raised its first round of major funding, securing $2 million from a range of investors and angels including *The New York Times*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In September 2016, the company published its first book, *Atlas Obscura: An Explorer's Guide to the World's Hidden Wonders* written by Foer, Thuras, and Ella Morton under Workman Publishing Company.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In 2019, Series B funding round raised $20 million from investors like Airbnb (lead investor), A+E Networks and New Atlantic Ventures.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In April 2025, Louise Story was announced as their CEO.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/atlas-obscura] In November, after disagreements with Story's direction for the company, Foer and Thuras were removed from the company board by shareholder vote.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Wedel is one of the most recognized chocolate confectioneries in Poland, having exclusive rights for the name *Ptasie mleczko*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Its owner created the original "bird's milk" in 1936.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Other confectionery producers also make similar candies named differently (e.g., *Alpejskie mleczko*, "Alpine milk").
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Nonetheless, *Ptasie mleczko* is often used to refer to similar candies with vanilla, cream, lemon or chocolate flavour.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Russia, *ptichye moloko* (птичье молоко) is both a popular candy and a famous soufflé cake derived from the Polish candy.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The brand was introduced in the 1960s during the Soviet era, and continues to be used by companies operating the factories which produced these candies and cakes since that time.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The confectionery is also produced in other post-Soviet states, such as Ukraine.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The concept of avian milk (Ancient Greek: ὀρνίθων γάλα, *ornithon gala*) stretches back to ancient Greece.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Aristophanes uses "the milk of the birds" in the plays *The Birds* and *The Wasps* as a proverbial rarity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The expression is also found in Strabo's *Geographica* where the island of Samos is described as a *blest country,* to which *those who praise it do not hesitate to apply the proverb that "it produces even bird's milk" (φέρει καί ὀρνίθων γάλα)*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] A similar expression *lac gallinaceum* (Latin for chicken's milk) was also later used by Petronius (38.1) and Pliny the Elder (Plin.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] 24) as a term for something of great rarity.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The idiom later became common in many languages and appeared in Slavic folk tales.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In one such tale, the beautiful princess tests the ardor and resourcefulness of her suitor by sending him out into the wilderness to find and bring back the one fantastical luxury she does not have: bird's milk.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In the fairy tale *Little Hare* by Aleksey Remizov (who wrote many imitations of traditional Slavic folk tales), the magic bird Gagana produces milk.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Whether any of these authors were aware of crop milk from some species of birds is unknown.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Bird's milk was first created in 1936 in Poland by Jan Wedel, owner of the E.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Wedel Chocolate Factory Museum in Warsaw, dedicated to the history of chocolate-making and the Wedel brand.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The museum includes a dedicated room devoted entirely to Ptasie Mleczko, where visitors can design their own packaging for the candy.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Russia, *ptichye moloko* was originally a type of confectionery introduced in 1967 in Vladivostok and in 1968 by the Rot Front factory in Moscow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] It became a hit, and mass production was started in 1975 by the *Krasny Oktyabr* confectionery factory in Moscow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Estonia, *linnupiim* (also bird's milk in Estonian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Kalev candy factory.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] This candy also uses agar-agar instead of gelatin as a thickening agent and comes in three flavors: chocolate, vanilla, and lemon.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In 2021, a special edition with grapefruit flavor was produced.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Moldova, *lapte de pasăre* (also bird's milk in Romanian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Bucuria candy factory.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Despite the name, the candy is not to be confused with the Romanian traditional dessert *lapte de pasăre*.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Lithuania, *paukščių pienas* (also bird's milk in Lithuanian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Vilniaus Pergalė factory.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In 1978, the popular candy was transformed into a cake by Vladimir Guralnik in Moscow's Praga Restaurant.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] This was a light sponge cake filled with an airy soufflé and topped with chocolate glaze.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] A distinct feature of the Russian recipe is the usage of agar-agar instead of gelatin as a thickening agent, which withstands the high temperature needed to melt down sugar into a syrup.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Initially, the restaurant produced trial batches of 20–30 cakes, but after six months the daily output was increased to 500 cakes.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] The recipe was quickly copied by other restaurants in Moscow, such as Moskva, Budapesht, and Ukraina.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In the 1980s, a special factory for Bird's milk cakes was built in the Novye Cheryomushky district in the south of Moscow.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Both the cake and the candy versions of the bird's milk are widely available to this date in supermarkets and specialty stores all over Russia.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] In Russia, *Птичье молоко* is a registered trademark of Rot Front, a member of United Confectioners.
[src:ptasie-mleczko/ptasie-mleczko] Other companies have been sued for using the name, even if they had used it in the Soviet Union.
